{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180810024006|854264785","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Jimmy_Duncan_(politician)","to":"Jimmy Duncan (politician)"}],"pages":{"1089396":{"pageid":1089396,"ns":0,"title":"Jimmy Duncan (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-12T18:41:44Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{for|other usages of the name John Duncan|John Duncan (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Jimmy Duncan\n|image        = John J. Duncan, official photo portrait.jpg\n|state        = [[Tennessee]]\n|district     = {{ushr|TN|2|2nd}}\n|term_start   = November 8, 1988\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[John Duncan Sr.]]\n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = John James Duncan Jr.\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1947|7|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Lebanon, Tennessee]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Lynn Duncan\n|education    = [[University of Tennessee]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[George Washington University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 1970\u20131987\n|rank         = [[File:US military captain's rank.gif|18px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]<ref name=\"AUSA2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf |title=Once a Soldier... Always a Soldier |year=2011 |work=Legislative Agenda |publisher=[[Association of the United States Army]] |accessdate=27 January 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021200011/http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf |archivedate=21 October 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n|unit         = [[United States Army Reserve]]<br>{{*}}[[Tennessee Army National Guard]]\n}}\n'''John James Duncan Jr.''' (born July 21, 1947) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TN|2}}, serving since 1988. A lawyer, former judge, and former long serving member of the [[Army National Guard]], he is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The district is based in [[Knoxville]]. [[Lincoln Memorial University]]'s [[Duncan School of Law]] in Knoxville is named after Duncan.<ref>http://www.knoxnews.com/news/2012/jan/19/judge-denies-lmus-request-to-force-aba-removal/#comments</ref> Duncan announced he will be not be running for reelection in 2018.\n\n==Early life, education, and legal career==\nDuncan was born in [[Lebanon, Tennessee]]. His \"paternal grandparents were small-areage farmers in [[Scott County, Tennessee|Scott County]], which in 1861 left Tennessee, refusing to follow the Volunteer State into the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]], and declared itself 'the Free and Independent [[state of Scott]].'\"<ref name=Kauffman>[[Bill Kauffman|Kauffman, Bill]] (2005-09-12) [http://www.amconmag.com/article/2005/sep/12/00011/ Volunteer Statesman], ''[[The American Conservative]]''</ref> Duncan's parents were Lois (Swisher) and [[John Duncan Sr.]], who \"hitchhiked into [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] with five dollars in his pocket,' and after an education at the [[University of Tennessee]] was elected mayor of Knoxville and then congressman.\"<ref name=Kauffman/> The elder Duncan was also a co-owner of the [[Tennessee Smokies|Knoxville Smokies]] of the \"[[Southern League (baseball)|Sally League]],\" for which his son \"was a batboy, a ball shagger, scoreboard operator, and, as a freshman at the University of Tennessee, the Smokies' public-address announcer.\"<ref name=Kauffman/> Duncan also worked as a grocery bagger and salesman at [[Sears]] while working his way through school. Duncan supported [[Barry Goldwater]]'s [[United States presidential election, 1964|1964]] presidential campaign, and sent the first paycheck he earned as a bagboy at the local [[A&P]] to the Goldwater campaign.<ref name=Kauffman/>\n\nDuncan graduated from the [[University of Tennessee at Knoxville]] in 1969 with a [[Bachelor of Journalism]] degree and subsequently received a [[Juris Doctor]] degree from [[George Washington University Law School]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1973 and was admitted to the [[bar (law)|bar]] that same year. He also served in the [[United States National Guard|Army National Guard]] from 1970 to 1987. He was an [[Lawyer|attorney]] in private practice until he became a state court [[judge]] in [[Knox County, Tennessee]], where he served from 1981 to 1988.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nHe was first elected to [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]] in 1988, in a [[special election]] to succeed his late father, [[John Duncan Sr.]], and elected to the seat for a full term in his own right the same day. He has been re-elected every two years since then from a district that has been held continuously by Republicans (or their antecedents) since 1859, and by a Duncan since his father was first elected in 1964.<ref name=Kauffman/> He has never faced a serious or well-funded challenge for reelection, and was reelected without major-party opposition in four consecutive elections (1994 through 2000).\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:U.S. Senators Bob Corker, Richard Burr, Lamar Alexander, Congressman John Duncan among others at the Great Smoky Mountains National Park in 2009.jpg|thumb|300px|U.S. Senators [[Bob Corker]], [[Richard Burr]], [[Lamar Alexander]], and Congressman John Duncan (third from right) among others at the [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]] in 2009]]\nDuncan voted against authorizing the 2003 [[2003 invasion of Iraq|War in Iraq]] based on opposition to what he believed to be an unnecessary foreign involvement. He also opposed and voted against a June 2006 House declaration in support of the war.<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003067352_vote17.html NWSource.com]</ref> He was one of the most [[conservatism|conservative]] Republicans to do so.<ref name=\"VoteSmart\">[http://www.vote-smart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=H3711103&type=category&category=Conservative Vote-smart.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710025447/http://www.vote-smart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=H3711103&type=category&category=Conservative |date=2007-07-10 }}</ref> Duncan later remarked that the [[Iraq War]] vote had been\n\n{{quote|a tough one for me. I have a very conservative Republican district. My Uncle Joe is one of the most respected judges in Tennessee: when I get in a really serious bind I go to him for advice. I had breakfast with him and my two closest friends and all three told me that I had to vote for the war. It's the only time in my life that I've ever gone against my Uncle Joe's advice. When I pushed that button to vote against the war back in 2002, I thought I might be ending my political career.<ref name=Kauffman/>}}\n\nDuncan was among only six Republicans to vote against funding for the [[Iraq War]] on May 24, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Bresnahan |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/05/25/politics/politico/thecrypt/main2852390.shtml |title=McNerney Takes Tough Vote On The War |work=CBS News |publisher=[[The Politico]] |date=2007-05-25}}</ref> Duncan voted, along with three other Republicans, to withdraw U.S. troops from Iraq by April 2008 on July 12, 2007.<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2007/roll624.xml</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2010, Duncan again joined three other Republicans in voting for the removal of troops from Afghanistan.<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2010/roll098.xml</ref> Duncan and [[Ron Paul]] were the only members of Congress to vote for the removal of troops from Afghanistan and against all recent bailout and stimulus bills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rlc.org/2009/03/26/17-courageous/ |title=17 courageous Congressmen voted against all bailouts &#124; Republican Liberty Caucus |publisher=Rlc.org |date=2009-03-26 |accessdate=2010-08-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813174538/http://www.rlc.org/2009/03/26/17-courageous/ |archivedate=2010-08-13 |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe has criticized [[neoconservatism]] and supports a [[non-interventionist]] foreign policy.<ref>https://duncan.house.gov/syria-intervention-mistake</ref>\n\nDuncan is a member of the [[Liberty Caucus]], a group of [[libertarianism|libertarian-minded]] congressional Republicans.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thelibertycommittee.org/|title= The Liberty Committee|accessdate=2007-06-24}}</ref>  Other members include [[Walter B. Jones]] of [[North Carolina]], [[Roscoe Bartlett]] of [[Maryland]], [[Scott Garrett]] of [[New Jersey]], and [[Jeff Flake]] of [[Arizona]]. A former neighbor of his district, [[Zach Wamp]] of the 3rd district, also belonged to the group during his tenure in the House.<ref name=\"nytimesmagazine\">{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/22/magazine/22Paul-t.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&oref=slogin |title = The Antiwar, Anti-Abortion, Anti-Drug-Enforcement-Administration, Anti-Medicare Candidacy of Dr. Ron Paul |first = Christopher |last = Caldwell |work = The New York Times Magazine |date = 2007-07-22 |accessdate = 2007-07-21}}</ref> \n\nDuncan voted against the [[Wall Street bailout]]. In a column he explained his vote stating he \"thought it would be better in the long run not to adopt the socialist approach.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Duncan Column on the Financial Bailout |date=October 20, 2008 |first=Jimmy |last=Duncan |url=http://www.house.gov/list/press/tn02_duncan/octfinbailout.shtml |work=Official House Site |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090529111544/http://www.house.gov/list/press/tn02_duncan/octfinbailout.shtml |archivedate=May 29, 2009 |df= }}</ref> The American Conservative Union gave Duncan a 96% score for his voting record in 2013, higher than any other federal Representative in Congress from Tennessee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conservative.org/legislative-ratings |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502002242/http://www.conservative.org/legislative-ratings |archivedate=2014-05-02 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Family Research Council]] has rated Duncan as a 92% or above since 2002<ref name=\"VoteSmart\"/> and the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] has rated him in equally positive terms.<ref name=\"VoteSmart\"/> In 2012, Duncan received the number one spot in the 435-member House in the National Taxpayers Union's (NTU) annual ranking of Congress, earning him the \"Taxpayer Hero\" award.\n\nDuncan is a frequent contributor to ''[[Chronicles (magazine)|Chronicles]]'' and ''[[The American Conservative]],'' both magazines associated with the [[paleoconservative]] movement.  He has also contributed to numerous trade publications and Capitol Hill newspapers. Duncan has also voiced public support for returning the gold standard.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2012/12/03/tennessee_goper_floats_return_to_the_gold_standard/ |title=Tennessee GOPer Floats Return to the Gold Standard |date=Dec 3, 2012 |work=Salon}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2016, Duncan endorsed [[Donald Trump]] for the Republican presidential nomination.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/04/rep-jimmy-duncan-endorses-donald-trump-222667 |title=Rep. Jimmy Duncan endorses Donald Trump |author=KRISTEN EAST |date=2016-04-30 |work=politico}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017 Representative Duncan refused to hold any town halls in his Congressional District after the election of President [[Donald Trump]], calling some of his constituents extremists, kooks and radicals.<ref>http://www.knoxnews.com/story/news/politics/2017/02/06/us-rep-jimmy-duncan-rejects-town-hall-requests-citing-extremists-kooks/97525388/</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2017, Duncan announced that he would not run for reelection in 2018. He wishes to spend more time with his family.<ref>http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_CONGRESS_DUNCAN?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]] (Vice Chairman)'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]] (Former Chairman)\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]] (Former Chairman)\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines and Hazardous Materials]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]\n** [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Subcommittee on Transportation and Public Assets]]\n** [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Subcommittee on National Security]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Friends of Scotland Caucus (Founding Co-Chairman)\n* Congressional Immigration Reform Caucus\n* [[Liberty Caucus]]\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n* Sportsmen's Caucus\n* [[Veterinary Medicine Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Veterinary Medicine Caucus|author=|url=https://schrader.house.gov/committees/veterinary-medicine-caucus.htm|format=| publisher=Veterinary Medicine Caucus |date=|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Constitution Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDuncan and his wife Lynn have four children and eight grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Duncan \u2013 Personal Life|url=http://www.duncan.house.gov/about-me/full-biography|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206025141/https://duncan.house.gov/about-me/full-biography|archivedate=2014-12-06|df=}}</ref>\n\nHe is also the brother of Tennessee State Senator [[Becky Duncan Massey]].\nHe currently resides in [[Grainger County]], Tennessee\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jimmy Duncan}}\n* [http://duncan.house.gov/ U.S. Congressman John J. Duncan Jr.] official U.S. House site\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Tennessee/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/John_Duncan_%5BR-2%5D|John J. Duncan Jr.}}\n* {{C-SPAN|johnduncan}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=d000533 | votesmart=27069 | fec=H8TN02069 | congress=john-duncan/322 }}\n* {{YouTube|nrLp03JIQhs|Video of Duncan explaining why supporting the Iraq war isn't conservative}} {{when|date=August 2013}}\n* {{YouTube|vjrYtWW0k6Y|Video and transcript of Duncan speech in the House explaining that the War on Terror is a Major Profit Center}}{{when|date=August 2013}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USR